  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_1' aria-label=\" Suvej Singh versus Ram Naresh and Ors. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('1','2025','2025_12_584_592','2025INSC1405'); ><font size='4'> <strong>SUVEJ SINGH<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>RAM NARESH AND ORS. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 12 S.C.R. 584</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 1405</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010006862025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : RAJESH BINDAL<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, MANMOHAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Whether the High Court misinterpreted the import of s.30, Uttar Pradesh Revenue Code, 2006 and erred in remanding the matter back for consideration afresh after affording due opportunity of hearing to all concerned. Headnotes&dagger; Uttar Pradesh Revenue Code, 2006 &ndash; map stood settled in the earlier proceedings between the parties in 2001 &ndash; However, the private respondents raised the same issue about 17 years later filing an application u/s.30/38 for correction of the map &ndash; Dismissed by Revenue Authorities &ndash; Writ Petition filed by private<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 09-12-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 14661/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('1','2025','2025_12_584_592','2025INSC1405','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class